Etiquette
---------
Posting is strict at AIDL. Please be relevant, accurate and non-commercial (FAQ Q12). Commercial posts are only allowed on Saturday, which is defined by Eastern Time. If you don't follow this rule, you might be banned.
How we treat different types of posts:
What we delete instantly:
  • Re-post from a page,
  • Re-post of an article which is already posted,
  • Copyrighted material, unless the author explicitly release the content
What we delete instantly on all days except Saturdays:
  • Promotion of another group, Facebook or not,
  • Promotion of conferences/events/products,
  • Job recruitment/solicitation,
  • Brand promotion: notice that any mentioning with your company name and brand within your post counted as promotion. This includes many company blog posts and exceptions only given to posts with great technical merits.
What we would redirect to ()
  • Questions which we have clearly answered in the FAQ, e.g. "How do I learn deep learning or AI?".
  • Questions which members can answered easily by Googling.
Discussion in the forum should be cordial and relevant to AI. Do not use foul language, or ad hominem attack to our members. We will ban you if you are rude to other members.

Frequently Asked Questions

Q0: (Meta) How do I use AIDL FAQ?
Learning AI requires you to absorb large amount of information. So the first requirement for you is to be able to read carefully. AIDL FAQ is a guide in the form of Q&A to explain how you can learn AI or deep learning properly. The most important questions are Q2-4. They are answers on "how to learn deep learning?" The next important question is Q10, which is about what language you should learn in order to learn AI/DL properly. Many of these questions have links which themselves are filled with links. For example. Learning Deep Learning - Top Five Lists (…/) is one of them.
Since the FAQ is mostly written by me (Arthur Chan) and I am limited in my knowledge. We also have a community-driven knowledge base called AIDL_KB (), you may submit suggested changes through git and curators will integrate your changes from time to time.
Q1: How do I start AI/ML/DL?
A:
Step 1: Learn some Math and Programming,
Step 2: Take some beginner classes. e.g. Try out Ng's Machine Learning.
Step 3: Find some problem to play with. Kaggle has tons of such tasks.
Iterate the above 3 steps until you become bored. From time to time you can share what you learn.
Here's a post which one of us (Arthur) wrote up. It summarizes his experience in learning machine learning and you might find it useful. ()
Q2: What is your recommended first class for ML?
A: Ng's Coursera, the CalTech edX class, the UW Coursera class is also pretty good.
Q3: What are your recommended classes for DL?
A: Go through at least 1 or 2 ML class, then go for Ng's deeplearning.ai class, Hinton's, Karparthay's, Socher's, LaRochelle's and de Freitas'. For deep reinforcement learning, go with Silver's and Schulmann's lectures. Also see Q4.
Q4: How do you compare different resources on machine learning/deep learning?
A: (Shameless self-promoting plug by Arthur) Here is an article, "Learning Deep Learning - Top-5 Resources" written by me (Arthur) on different resources and their prerequisites. I refer to it couple of times at AIDL, and you might find it useful: (You can find it at Guide).
Other than my own list, here are some very good lists I recommend you to read through as well,
  • YerevaNN Lab's "A Guide to Deep Learning" () - concepts are ranked in terms of difficulty, very handy for learners.
  • Deep Learning Drizzle.
  • A16Z AI playbook: - a list which placed more focus on AI, it complements the other lists I quote.
  • Reddit's machine learning FAQ has another list of great resources as well.
Q5: How do I use machine learning technique X with language L?
A: Google is your friend. You might also see a lot of us referring you to Google from time to time. That's because your question is best to be solved by Google.
Q6: Explain concept Y. List 3 properties of concept Y.
A: Google. Also we don't do your homework. If you couldn't Google the term though, it's fair to ask questions.
Q7: What is the most recommended resources on deep learning on computer vision?
A: cs231n. 2016 is the one I will recommend. Most other resources you will find are derivative in nature or have glaring problems.
Q8: What is the prerequisites of Machine Learning/Deep Learning?
A: Mostly Linear Algebra and Calculus I-III. In Linear Algebra, you should be good at eigenvectors and matrix operation. In Calculus, you should be quite comfortable with differentiation. You might also want to have a primer on matrix differentiation before you start because it's a topic which is seldom touched in an undergraduate curriculum.
Some people will also argue Topology as important and having a Physics and Biology background could help. But they are not crucial to start.

A: Here are few good lists:
  • Another classic is deeplearning.net's reading list:
  • AIDL has a curated github as well, maintained by members:
  • Awesome deep learning papers have the most cited papers:
Q10: What is the best/most recommended language in Deep Learning/AI?
A: This is one of the most frequently asked questions and it re-emerged from time to time. So here are few couple of useful point of view:
In general, if you are working on computer, you will need to switch between languages from time to time. So arguing about language and which is better is not a wise thing. If we want to give the best advice, perhaps the answer is you should just learn as many of them as possible.
Of course, your time is limited. So AIDL usually recommend python as your first choice. Python is cited as a good language for AI/DL because it has the best support of libraries. Most ML libraries from python links with C/C++. So you get the best of both flexibility and speed.
Other also cites Java (deeplearning4j), Lua (Torch), Lisp, Golang, R. It really depends on your purpose. Practical concerns such as code integration, your familiarity with a language usually dictates your choice. R deserves special mention because it was widely used in some brother fields such as data science and it is gaining popularity.
Finally, there is Matlab/Octave, it is also useful to learn because many Coursera ML's class is Matlab-based. e.g. Ng's class and Hinton's class. Sure, you can finish them in python, but there are much re-implementation in the process.
Q11: I am bad at Math/Programming. Can I still learn A.I/D.L?
A: Mostly you can tag along, but at a certain point, if you don't understand the underlying Math, you won't be able to understand what you are doing. Same for programming, if you never implement one, or trace one yourself, you will never truly understand why an algorithm behave a certain way.
So what if you feel you are bad at Math? Don't beat yourself too much. Take Barbara Oakley's class on "Learning How to Learn", you will learn more about tough subjects such as Mathematics, Physics and Programming.

Q19: Hi everyone, I really want to build a chatbot? Can anyone tell me more?
A: This is frequently asked. But then we usually don't give detail answers. So first of all, despite what people tell you, machine doesn't really know how to respond like human yet. It is a difficult problem. We can only tell you some approaches to go forward.
The first approach is to write a bunch of ifs, and then each of them give users some answers. This result in programmer crafting a giant state machine like structure of the program. There are many abstraction framework which helps you to create this kind of program much faster, you can try AIML for example. AIDL seldom put focus on this kind of method, because it is mostly programming/lookup. And there is not much machine learning about it.
The second approach is to gather a bunch of question/answer pairs, then try to train machine to learn it. You can use something like a neural network machine translation (NNMT) method or any translation models you like to train such a model. But then how do you come up with good and relevant answer is tough. So that's why it is still a research topic.
You can think the second approach could be extended to many other use cases of DL, e.g. you can stuff a reading comprehension program and later it can answer question. But then notice that you are still not solving the question of how to give natural and relevant dialogue.
Q20: Hi everyone, would you give me an idea for my AI project, FYP, thesis and competition?
A: Don't be lazy. Coming up with an idea is part of the training if you decide to do a project, FYP, or write a thesis, or join a competition. In fact, if you decide to join an AI competition, it will be cheating if we are the ones who come up with the idea.
But it's legit to ask how you can come up with ideas. Usually there are two ways:
1, Go to check out other people's idea, then twist it.
2, Go to solve a problem that you feel about. e.g. a lot of science project winners won because their love ones have diseases. And a deep learning-based approach help the process to diagnose the problem.
If you are out of ideas, then consider few things: 1) ask smarter people what inspire them to come up with an idea, 2) read a lot, 3) don't work on technical problem for a while and do some artsy stuffs. All 3 methods can give you a lot of inspirations.
Q21: Is AI just a bunch of ifs? LOL, I saw a meme posted in my favorite AI group said so.
Well, some machine learning algorithms do use condition statements. e.g. algorithms of decision tree would use a sets of pre-trained questions to classify a dataset. In those cases, you do write an if in your ML program.
So is chatbot, a lot of them are really just a bunch of ifs. It goes like if I parse a certain phrase, then I give a certain response.
But then, decision tree and chatbots are just specific type of AI/ML, how about techniques like neural networks? Oh, if you delve into the source code they are the most if-free function you will ever seen. Mostly neural network's internal code are based on matrix computations. So, more like a for-loop?
Then you might ask, "Oh I am so-smart-so-I-am-going-to-write-an-if-statement to change the values of these matrix under certain situations." Don't ever do it, most of the training algorithm faithfully represent the population of your training data. You manually change the value would easily screw up the program.
Then why do people talk about AI is just a bunch of ifs all the time? Part of it is most people these days don't delve into the source of ML programs. And what else is better than laughing at some supposedly smart AI algorithms? So saying AI is a bunch of ifs portray you as a seemingly wise person.
Q22: Is AI going to kill all humans? I heard Elon Musk said AI will become an existential threat, if Elon Musk said that, it must be absolute truth, right?
Throughout the history of human beings, when new technologies are developed, then fear would easily grow among people. The fear of AI, as portrayed on media, are mostly irrational. AI, as of this writing (2019), really can listen and see well enough. And given a large amount of data, it classifies well. These are great functionalities, but it seems far from the omnipotent superintelligent AI that is portrayed in Hollywood.
Here is one silly argument but it's worthwhile to debunk: "If a super-intelligent AI does exists, it would hide itself from humanity." Just substitute "AI" with "refrigerator" or "penguin" or anything else, you may argue that anything exists.
But are there any safety issues of using AI? There are many. e.g. AI is increasingly weaponized. Machine learning algorithm such as face recognition also invade citizens' privacy. Lastly, training data of AI algorithms are often biased towards certain groups of population, which can likely create fairness issue in the future. These are real-issues, and researchers are indeed making effort to fix them. And we at AIDL, are happy to discuss them.
Is it possible that super-intelligent AI will emerge? I personally think so too. But it's likely to be 100 Turing Prize away. Check out Nick Bolstrom's Superintelligence? It has a good philosophical arguments on why superintelligence would appear.
Finally, about Elon. Well, he is certainly a smart guy, but then he is never an AI expert. One of his guys, Andrej Karpathy is pretty good though. And Karpathy's speculation of AGI is something you like to read.

PSA: One thing I can tell you about COVID-19: Even the virus' potency and high reproduction number doesn't deter spammers of AIDL.

Indeed, since AIDL decided to give special exception (under #specialexception), there are many spams related to COVID-19. Here is a rough guideline on what we will accept/reject:

* News, tutorial on AI - as always we will accept them if they are quality and not a repost.

* News on how AI help on COVID-19 - we are interested, but they have to be new. e.g. We learn about CORD-19 five times already. So no need to do another write up for us.

* Non-profit effort to help on COVID-19 - this will be accepted under special exception category. But we want to refrain from reposting a certain organization too often.

* News on COVID-19 - that we will only accept infographics, statistics and numerical results. In particular, we will refrain from accepting medical information about the virus in our forum. My advice: you shouldn't even share those info to your friends unless you are a doctor. Only medical authority should give those advice.

* Others junk posts such as free laptops, free iPads, free ML courses - if you post them, we will make sure you are banned.

This post will be pinned as Announcement X.

H/T Yoshua Bengio

"Pressed by several, including Gary Marcus, to define deep learning, here is something else I wrote to help clarify and respond to Gary's misunderstandings of what is deep learning.

Deep learning is inspired by neural networks of the brain to build learning machines which discover rich and useful internal representations, computed as a composition of learned features and functions.

Note how this definition is a goal and does not say much about HOW we achieve that. Everything in my NeurIPS talk is really about adding priors to help learn better high-level representations. Because the 'how' is open-ended, because it's an open problem how to achieve that goal best, the term deep learning is indeed aspirational, like 'AI' or 'machine learning'. On the quest to achieve that, we explore different ideas, methods, algorithms, architectures, training objectives and frameworks, etc and the underlying principles (which correspond to priors about the world or the functions needed). We have gathered many interesting ones already, and they are already amazingly useful, but much more needs to be done.

This view is not really new, this is how I have been thinking for decades. Of course when you write a paper, the focus is always on something more concrete, like a particular architecture, task, optimization method, etc. But the soul of the community is precisely in this larger picture, this shared objective. And of course, the term is not defined by any one person but by its usage in the community."

Pressed by several, including Gary Marcus, to define deep learning, here is something else I wrote to help clarify and respond to Gary's misunderstandings of what is deep learning.

Deep learning is inspired by neural networks of the brain to build learning machines which discover rich and useful internal representations, computed as a composition of learned features and functions.

Note how this definition is a goal and does not say much about HOW we achieve that. Everything in my NeurIPS talk is really about adding priors to help learn better high-level representations. Because the 'how' is open-ended, because it's an open problem how to achieve that goal best, the term deep learning is indeed aspirational, like 'AI' or 'machine learning'. On the quest to achieve that, we explore different ideas, methods, algorithms, architectures, training objectives and frameworks, etc and the underlying principles (which correspond to priors about the world or the functions needed). We have gathered many interesting ones already, and they are already amazingly useful, but much more needs to be done.

This view is not really new, this is how I have been thinking for decades. Of course when you write a paper, the focus is always on something more concrete, like a particular architecture, task, optimization method, etc. But the soul of the community is precisely in this larger picture, this shared objective. And of course, the term is not defined by any one person but by its usage in the community.

#meta Some jargons we use at AIDL:

OoT : Out of topic. It usually means your post is not relevant to our forum.

"Saturday": It means your post would not be accepted on weekdays, but acceptable on Saturday. It also gives a hint to vigilant members that there is no need to report the post.

The Page and The Group: What you seeing here is the AIDL Group. But AIDL also has a Page. Usually we direct members to our Group for posting/discussion.

meta: Those are more messages from admin/mod. Like this one.

OP: The original poster.

Page-repost and Group-repost: i.e. You shared a post from a post which is already shared on another page/group. We frown upon this practice because many of these re-shares don't add values to the content. More often, rather than spreading information, it is a practice for publicizing a page/group.

FAQ: In the context of AIDL, FAQ is the common knowledge base which answer important questions for beginners. Some of the questions are repeatedly asked and answered. So everyone expected beginners to go check out FAQ first.

Etiquette: Etiquette contains rules you should follow before posting. AIDL is strict about posting so we suggest you to read through the section. Both Etiquette and FAQ reside at the first Announcement of the group.

"exception": We occasionally grant exception to posts which we believe is worthwhile to the group. Usually it has to do with charity, specific cause or their potential impact to AI/DL.

"special exception": In unusual circumstances, we would allow OOT technical posts in our forum. This usually relates to public crisis. If that's the case, we will mark the post as hash tag specialexception.

A Non-exhaustive List of Irrelevant Topics for AIDL

#meta It's Saturday. So I want to write a more light-hearted post on the *irrelevant* posts which admins/mods filter out daily. To give some context, I wake up everyday and find 50+ submitted posts. (The daily total is around 100-120) Sadly, even if we have been stressing that "you should only submit posts relevant to AI/DL", the message doesn't seem to come through to members, especially new members.

As a result, I decided to compile a list of topics which has nothing to do with AI/DL, yet they were sent to us for approval. My purpose? 1) These topics are both sad and funny; 2) It gives you some ideas on what kind of posts we go through daily; 3) There might be topics you passionately believe it should be included. Well, then we can argue about it. (Actually, please don't.)

This becomes Announcement 7 which allows me to quote it from time to time.

So here we are, irrelevant posts submitted to us:
- Your selfies,
- Your partner’s selfies,
- You and your friends singing together,
- Your latest album,
- Your Zen buddhist enlightenment,
- Your feeling that there is a superior being such that AI is just impossible,
- Why certain world religion is the best/the worst,
- Why Nicki Minaj should not be more relevant to Taylor Swift (or as you aptly called her "TayTay"),
- Your religious inner awakening,
- You want to confess your love to your crush, but you do not know how to say it. And data-driven approach doesn't have any appeal to you,
- You want to hack a password protected computer, but do not know how to, nor the term n-gram doesn't ring a bell to you in this character guessing problem,
- Your magical heal for a super-duper disease,
- How mindfulness can change one's life,
- Pictures of surgery and how you save human life meantime,
- Why a certain person is your personal hero,
- Great opportunities for members to buy cheap basketball shoes,
- Real estate opportunities,
- Selling us on-line class which you ripped off from one of the legit sites.
- Why cryptocurrency is changing our lives,
- Who is who has saved your life to make your learn how to trade cryptos, and now you become a self-made man,
- How can we work from home yet make a comfortable living,
- Cybersecurity and infosec which is not relevant to AI,
- 3-D printing,
- Superconductivity,
- Physics topic which has a lot of Math, but has nothing to do with AI/deep learning,
- Basic programming technique such as how to brilliantly use a for-loop to solve a problem,
- Why Biology and Chemistry is so much fun!,
- Mental Math tricks such as how you can multiply a number ended with 5 quickly,
- Brain twister which you believe only genius can answer them,
- Tricks of Java Programming
- etc (Again, this list is non-exhaustive.)

Arthur Chan

Announcement about Posting on AIDL:

From Jun 10, 2018, all posts would be first approved by admins/mods before they can appear in the main forum. This changes our long-time policy of allowing postings from anyone and only remove them afterward. Read below for further discussion.

Details: Since AIDL's inception 2 years ago, we have been using a free posting system which allows members to post anything, but only close/remove posts afterward. Unfortunately, our surprisingly rapid growth made this systems unscalable. It's getting harder to manually remove all spammy commercial or irrelevant posts from our forum. Furthermore, since posts would pop up on members feed, these irrelevant posts has been hurting our group's reputation as an informative news source.

Perhaps the more important reason here is that members have voiced their concerns on repetitive beginners posts. A lot of more professional members are gone because of the reason. So we think it's time to take some actions.

Our change will make all posts go through admin first before posting. We will still keep general discussion, but they will only appear in several designated threads from the forum. This just follows the example of our FAQ thread.

For any questions, feel free to contact admins/mods of AIDL. We will pin this post as the Third Announcement of the group.

Thanks,
Arthur Chan
